{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Nu5uSs4TxkKRoo8dcVyKxs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CWuK3MZAsxrYMcr7cwPcw6","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure occurs in how the tool interprets git's rename detection output. Git uses similarity heuristics to identify renames, and the tool must correctly parse that output and categorize it separately from delete+add pairs. A pure unit test mocking git command output might use simplified formats, missing edge cases in how git actually reports renames (e.g., renames with modifications, similarity thresholds). A real git repository with an actual rename operation verifies the tool correctly interacts with git's subprocess and handles the real output format.","test_description":"Create a temporary git repository, perform a file rename operation using 'git mv <old> <new>', commit the change, then run the tool to analyze recent changes. Verify that the renamed file appears in a 'renamed' category only and is not also counted in separate 'deleted' and 'added' categories.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires a real git repository and real git operations, which is integration-level infrastructure. The test would fail if the tool misinterprets git's rename status output.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.35,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is the tool crashing or producing incorrect output when git diff reports binary files. Git outputs special markers for binary files (e.g., 'Binary files differ'). A unit test could mock this output, but wouldn't verify the tool handles real binary file scenarios (actual binary content, git's detection logic). The tool must robustly parse git's diff output for binary files without crashing, and this requires wiring the git interaction with the parsing logic against a real repository containing actual binary files.","test_description":"Create a temporary git repository, add and commit a binary file (e.g., a PNG image or compiled binary), then run the tool to analyze changes. Verify that the tool completes without crashing, produces a valid report, and the binary file is counted in the appropriate output category.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires a real git repository with actual binary content and real git subprocess output. It would fail if the tool crashes or silently ignores binary files.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is the tool erroring or producing malformed output when analyzing a repository with no commit history. Git commands behave differently on empty repositories (no HEAD, no refs), and the tool must handle this edge case. While this could be mocked at the unit level, a real empty git repository tests whether the tool correctly invokes git commands (which may fail gracefully on empty repos) and produces correct output. Integration testing with a real repository verifies the tool doesn't assume the existence of commits or refs.","test_description":"Create a temporary git repository with no commits (initial state, no HEAD), run the tool to analyze changes, and verify that the output is an empty report structure (not an error, crash, or invalid JSON/structured format).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires a real git repository in the initial state. It would fail if the tool crashes or produces malformed output when git has no commits.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a correctness test that verifies the tool accurately counts adds, deletes, modifies, and renames across multiple commits. A unit test mocking git output could use a simplified history, missing edge cases in git's output format or the tool's accumulation logic (e.g., counting multiple edits to the same file, handling file moves across directories, handling mass deletions). A real git repository with a known, deterministic history verifies the tool's counting logic against actual git data and catches subtle bugs in aggregation or interpretation.","test_description":"Create a temporary git repository with a deterministic sequence of commits that perform known operations: add 3 files in commit 1, modify 2 of them in commit 2, delete 1 file in commit 3, rename 1 file in commit 4. Run the tool to analyze the commit range and verify the output counts exactly match: 3 additions, 2 modifications, 1 deletion, 1 rename (and 0 of any other category).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires a real git repository with multiple commits and real git log/diff output. It would fail if the tool miscounts, double-counts, or misses any change type.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is the tool producing different outputs for the same changes depending on whether they are staged (git index) or unstaged (working directory). The tool's logic must normalize or abstract away this distinction. Git reports staged and unstaged changes differently in 'git diff' (unstaged) vs 'git diff --cached' (staged). The tool must correctly invoke the right git commands or normalize the output. This requires wiring the git interface with the report logic against a real repository with actual staged/unstaged changes; mocking both states might miss normalization bugs.","test_description":"Create a temporary git repository with some committed baseline. Create new file changes (modifications, additions) but do not stage them, run the tool and capture output. Then stage all changes using 'git add', run the tool again, and verify the output is identical in both cases (same counts, same categories, same file lists).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires a real git repository where files can be staged and unstaged, and real git diff output for both states. It would fail if the tool uses only 'git diff --cached' (staged) and misses unstaged changes, or vice versa.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13602,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13602},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5bfe1fd-6868-444d-bf6c-bb3cc92d1a3e","uuid":"3ce9d147-9018-4c2f-8f09-03dbd07e025f"}
